# React Project Rules

## Architecture

The project follows a modular structure under `src/`:

- `core/` - Global core functionality used across the entire app
  - `auth/` - Authentication and authorization logic
  - `form/` - Abstract form components and utilities
  - Other app-wide utilities and configurations
- `modules/` - Logical feature modules
  - `admin/` - Admin feature module
    - `layouts/` - Admin-specific layouts (with header, footer, sidebar, etc.)
    - `pages/` - Admin page components
  - `login/` - Login feature module
    - `layouts/` - Login-specific layouts
    - `pages/` - Login page components
- `ui/` - Shared UI components library
  - `components/` - Reusable components (button, input, label, toast, etc.)

### Component Structure

Each unit (component, layout, page, etc.) may contain the following folders:

- `constants/` - Constants and configuration values
- `enums/` - Enumeration types
- `components/` - Sub-components specific to this unit
- `forms/` - Form components specific to this unit (for pages only)
  - Each form may contain `schemas/`, `types/`, and `constants/` subfolders
- `api/` - API layer specific to this unit (for pages only)
  - `mutations/` - Mutation functions for data modifications
- `types/` - TypeScript type definitions

Example component structure:
```
ui/button/
  ├── Button.tsx
  ├── constants/
  │   └── button.constants.ts
  ├── enums/
  │   └── button.enums.ts
  ├── types/
  │   └── button.types.ts
  └── components/
      └── ButtonIcon.tsx
```

Example page with forms and API:
```
pages/login/
  ├── Login.tsx
  ├── forms/
  │   └── login-form/
  │       ├── LoginForm.tsx
  │       ├── schemas/
  │       │   └── login-form.schema.ts
  │       ├── types/
  │       │   └── login-form.types.ts
  │       └── constants/
  │           └── login-form.constants.ts
  └── api/
      └── mutations/
          └── login.mutation.ts
```

## Component Conventions

- Use TypeScript for all components
- Use function components with hooks (no class components)
- **Use arrow function syntax for all components**: `const ComponentName = () => { ... }`
- Name files with `.tsx` extension
- Use PascalCase for component names and files (e.g., `Button.tsx`, `LoginLayout.tsx`)
- Export components as default exports
- Export types as named exports (e.g., `export type { ButtonProps }`)

## Props and Types

- Always type component props with TypeScript interfaces or inline types
- For layout components that wrap content, accept `children` prop typed as `React.ReactNode`
- Example:
  ```tsx
  const Layout = ({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) => {
    return <div>{children}</div>;
  };
  ```

## File Organization

- Place global, app-wide functionality in `core/` (e.g., authentication, routing, API clients, abstract form components)
- Keep feature-specific modules in `modules/` (e.g., `modules/admin/`, `modules/login/`)
- Each module contains its own `layouts/` and `pages/` directories
- Layouts may have their own `components/` subfolder for layout-specific components (header, footer, sidebar)
- Pages may have their own `forms/` subfolder for page-specific form components
  - Each form can contain its own `schemas/`, `types/`, and `constants/` subfolders
- Pages may have their own `api/` subfolder for page-specific API logic
  - `api/mutations/` contains mutation functions for data modifications
- Pages may also have a `components/` subfolder for other page-specific components
- Place truly reusable UI components in `ui/`
- Place abstract form components and utilities in `core/form/`
- Each component unit can contain: `constants/`, `enums/`, `components/`, `types/`, and (for pages) `forms/` and `api/` subfolders as needed

## Imports

- Prefer named imports from React when needed: `import { useState, useEffect } from 'react'`
- Use relative imports for local components with `.tsx` extension
- Group imports: React/external libraries first, then local imports
- Example:
  ```tsx
  import { useState } from "react";
  import AuthGuard from "../../../core/auth/guards/AuthGuard.tsx";
  import AdminLayout from "../layouts/AdminLayout.tsx";
  import Button from "@ui/button/Button.tsx";
  ```

## Styling

The project uses Tailwind CSS v4+ with custom design tokens:

- **Tailwind CSS**: Utility-first styling via `@tailwindcss/vite` plugin
- **Custom colors**: Define in `main.css` using `@theme` directive
  - Available custom colors: `primary`, `secondary`, `accent`
  - Usage: `bg-primary`, `text-secondary`, `border-accent`
  - Supports opacity modifiers: `bg-primary/50`, `text-accent/80`
- **Container pattern**: Use `mx-auto w-full max-w-[1280px]` for centered 1280px containers
- **Cursor styling**: Add `cursor-pointer` to interactive elements

## UI Component Library

The project uses Base UI (unstyled primitives) styled with Tailwind CSS:

- **Base UI**: Provides accessible, unstyled components (`@base-ui/react`)
- **Component pattern**: Wrap Base UI primitives with Tailwind styles in `ui/`

### Available UI Components

- **Input**: Text input with validation states (`data-invalid`, `data-focused`, etc.)
  - Accepts standard HTML input props (type, placeholder, id, etc.)
- **Button**: Five variants (primary, secondary, outline, ghost, destructive)
  - Usage: `<Button variant="outline">Submit</Button>`
  - Includes cursor-pointer styling
- **Label**: Form labels with consistent styling
  - Usage: `<Label htmlFor="email">Email</Label>`
  - Supports dark mode
- **Toast**: Notification system with Provider, Root, Title, Description, Close, Action parts

### Creating new UI components

1. Create folder: `src/ui/component-name/`
2. Add `ComponentName.tsx` wrapping Base UI primitive (if applicable)
3. Optionally add subfolders as needed:
   - `constants/component-name.constants.ts` - Style constants and configuration (export `baseClassName` with Tailwind classes)
   - `types/component-name.types.ts` - TypeScript type definitions (re-export/extend Base UI types or React HTML attributes)
   - `enums/component-name.enums.ts` - Enumeration types (e.g., variants, sizes)
   - `components/` - Sub-components if needed
4. Export default component and types from main file
5. Component should accept `className` prop for additional styling and merge with base classes

### Form Field Pattern

When creating form fields with labels:

```tsx
<div className="flex flex-col gap-2">
  <Label htmlFor="fieldId">Field Label</Label>
  <Input id="fieldId" type="text" placeholder="Enter value" />
</div>
```
